[[Field Marshal]] '''John Byng, 1st Earl of Strafford''', [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Royal Guelphic Order|GCH]], [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC (I)]] (1772 &ndash; 3 June 1860) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Peerage|peer]], politician and soldier.

==Early years==
Byng was the third son of Major George Byng,<ref name=heath>Heathcote, p. 60</ref> son of the Hon. [[Robert Byng]], third son of [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington]].<ref name=heath/> His mother was Anne, a maternal granddaughter of the [[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Strafford|1st Earl of Strafford]] of the first creation. [[George Byng (1764&ndash;1847)|George Byng]] was his elder brother. In 1793, he joined the [[33rd Regiment of Foot]] as an [[Ensign (rank)|Ensign]]<ref name=heath/> and fought under [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Col. Arthur Wellesley]] (later [[Duke of Wellington (title)|Duke of Wellington]]) in [[Flanders]] from 1793<U+2013>95 and was wounded at [[Battle of Geldermalsen|Geldermalsen]]. From 1797 to 1798, he was [[aide-de-camp]] to [[Richard William Howard Vyse|General Vyse]] in [[Ireland]], where he was again wounded, this time in the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]].<ref name=heath/> In 1800, he became a [[Major]] in the [[60th Regiment of Foot]],<ref name=heath/> a [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] in the [[29th Regiment of Foot]] a few months later,<ref name=heath/> and was stationed at [[City of Halifax|Halifax, Nova Scotia]] from 1802 to 1804. In 1804, he transferred to the [[3rd Regiment of Foot Guards]] and took part in the [[Hanoverian Expedition]] in 1805, the [[Siege of Copenhagen]] in 1807 and the [[Walcheren Expedition]] in 1809.<ref name=heath/>

==Napoleonic Wars==
In 1811, Byng was promoted to a [[Brigadier-General]] and fought in the [[Peninsular War]] under [[Rowland Hill, 1st Viscount Hill|General Hill]]. He was engaged in [[Spain]] and southern [[France]] at the battles of [[Battle of Vitoria|Vitoria]],<ref name=heath/> [[Battle of the Pyrenees|the Pyrenees]],<ref name=heath/> Pamplona (where he was wounded), [[Battle of Nivelle|the Nivelle]] (where he was again wounded)<ref name=heath/> and [[Battle of the Nive|the Nive]] in 1813.<ref name=heath/> He fought in actions at [[Espelette]], [[Garris]], [[Battle of Orthez|Orthez]],<ref name=heath/> [[Aire-sur-l'Adour]] and [[Battle of Toulouse (1814)|Toulouse]] in 1814.<ref name=heath/> During the [[Battle of Waterloo]]<ref name=heath/> he led a brigade of Guards ([[Coldstream Guards|2/2nd Guards]] and [[Scots Guards|2/3rd Guards]]) in the 1st Division. He was involved in the advance on [[Paris]] soon after and occupied the heights of [[Montmartre]]. He was appointed a [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] in 1815, twice received thanks from both [[Houses of Parliament]], was promoted to a [[Lieutenant-General]] in 1825 and was appointed a [[Royal Guelphic Order|GCH]] in 1826.  In recognition of his services, he was awarded the [[Army Gold Cross]], with one clasp, for the battles of Vitoria, the Pyrenees, Nivelle, Nive, and Orthez; the [[Military General Service Medal]] with one clasp for Toulouse; and the [[Waterloo Medal]].

==Ireland and politics==
In 1828, Byng was appointed [[Commander-in-Chief, Ireland]]<ref name=heath/> and admitted to the [[Privy Council of Ireland]] the same year. After leaving Ireland in 1831, he was appointed a [[Order of the Bath|GCB]] and switched to politics, being elected as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]] in [[Dorset]], a seat he held until he was raised to the [[Peerage]] as '''Baron Strafford''' in 1835.<ref name=heath/> In 1841, he was promoted to a [[General]] He was further raised in the Peerage as '''Viscount Enfield''' and '''Earl of Strafford''' 1843<ref name=heath/> and inherited [[Wrotham Park]] from his eldest brother in 1847. In 1855, he was further promoted to the highest military rank of [[Field Marshal]] and on his death five years later in 1860, his titles passed to his eldest son, [[George Byng, 2nd Earl of Strafford|Viscount Enfield]].<ref name=heath/>

==Family==
On 14 June 1804, Byng married heiress, Mary Mackenzie<ref name=heath/> and they had one child:

*[[George Byng, 2nd Earl of Strafford|Hon. George Stevens Byng, later styled Viscount Enfield, later 2nd Earl of Strafford]] (1806<U+2013>1886)

Byng's first wife died from complications of the birth shortly after and on 9 May 1808, he married Marianne James<ref name=heath/> (the second daughter of [[Walter James Head|Sir Walter James Head, Bart.]] and maternal granddaughter of the [[Charles Pratt, 1st Earl Camden|1st Earl Camden]]) and they had four children:

*Hon. William Frederick (d. 1877)
*Lady Harriet Frances (d. 1873), married [[Charles Ramsden|Capt. Charles Ramsden]].
*Hon. Frances (d. 1846), married [[Henry Tufnell]].
*Lady Caroline Frances (d. 27 May 1898), mar. 18 Aug 1835 [[Walter George Stirling|Sir Walter George Stirling, Bart.]]

